14 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
15 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
16 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3-9-100 of Title 27A, unless
17 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
18 This act shall be known and may be cited as the “Oklahoma
19 Invasive Woody Species Stewardship for State-Leased Lands Act”.
20 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
21 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3-9-101 of Title 27A, unless
22 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
23 A. As used in this act, “invasive woody species” means a native
24 or non-native tree or shrub species that threatens and causes harm
Req. No. 1963 Page 1

1 to t he environment, water resources, or economy. Invasive woody
2 species include, but are not limited to, Juniperus virginiana
3 (Eastern Redcedar), Juniperus scopulorum (Rocky Mountain juniper),
4 Juniperus monosperma (oneseed juniper), and Tamarix ramosissima
5 (salt cedar).
6 B. As established in the Oklahoma Constitution, the
7 Commissioners of the Land Office are responsible for the management
8 of the permanent school fund and the management of trust assets for
9 the exclusive purpose of providing maximum benefits of current and
10 future beneficiaries. Invasive woody species threaten to, and have
11 caused harmed to, the environment, water resources, and the economy,
12 including having caused harm to and devaluing the trust assets and
13 the permanent school fund. Invasive woody species are likely to
14 cause further harm to and further devalue the Office’s trust assets
15 of the permanent school fund. In order to protect and maintain the
16 value of trust assets of the permanent school fund, and to manage
17 trust assets for the benefit of current and future beneficiaries,
18 the Office is hereby authorized to remove and manage invasive woody
19 species as provided in this act.
20 C. By December 15 of each year, the Office shall identify and
21 prioritize trust lands that have been harmed and devalued by
22 invasive woody species and shall submit a management plan to the
23 Oklahoma Conservation Commission, outlining the strategy that the
24
Req. No. 1963 Page 2

1 Comm issioners of the Land Office intend to employ for the removal
2 and ongoing maintenance of invasive woody species on trust lands.
3 D. The Office shall be authorized to:
4 1. Enter into programs run by, in coordination with, or in
5 contract with the Oklahoma Conservation Commission, other state or
6 federal agencies, or entities lawfully engaging in prescribed burns
7 for the removal and management of invasive woody species;
8 2. Contract with vendors for the removal and management of
9 invasive woody species;
10 3. Contract with its lessee for the removal and management of
11 invasive woody species; and
12 4. Engage in any other lawful activity for the removal and
13 management of invasive woody species.
14 E. By February 15 each year, the Commissioners of the Land
15 Office shall submit electronically a report to the Legislature
16 detailing the actions taken and the program made under the
17 provisions of this act.
18 F. Beginning in fiscal year 2026, and each subsequent fiscal
19 year, the Commissioners of the Land Office shall expend no greater
20 than One Million Dollars ($1,000,000.00) to carry out the provisions
21 of this act. The Office may also receive state resources through
22 coordination with the Oklahoma Conservation Commission or other
23 state agencies.
